@Node "Installation" "Event!.guide/Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Installation

The most easiest way to install Event!  is by using the provided
Install-Script.  You will need the Installer by Commodore for this purpose
but this should be no problem since Commodore made it freely distributable
for users.  The Install Script will copy Event!  either to your
SYS:WBStartup-directory or any other directory.  If you don't specify
SYS:WBStartup as directory you will be asked if Event!  should be started
from "s:user-startup".  If you answer "Yes" the necessary lines will be
added to your "s:user-startup".  So Event!  will get started every time
your system boots up.

If you can't use Installer you should at least copy the program file
to the desired place and the necessary catalogs to LOCALE: if you own
WB 2.1 or higher and want to use localization.

@EndNode

@Node "Starting Event!" "Event!.guide/Starting Event!"
@Toc "Main"

Starting Event!

@{"From Workbench" Link "From Workbench"} 
@{"From Shell" Link "From Shell"} 
@{"Important Note" Link "Important Note"} 

@EndNode

@Node "From Workbench" "Event!.guide/From Workbench"
@Toc "Starting Event!"

From Workbench        

Simply move Event! into your SYS:WBStartup directory. If you own
the Installer-Utility by Commodore, simply click on the
@{"Install Event!" Link "Installation"}-icon and any necessary files
will be copied.

The ToolTypes for Workbench Start are the same as the
@{"Shell arguments" Link "From Shell"}.

Additionally you may use the following tooltypes:

STARTPRI

set  this lower than the STARTPRI of RexxMast if you start RexxMast
from WBStartup.

TOOLPRI

The initial TaskPriority of the Event! main task. May be overwritten
by MAINPRI while reading in the config.

CREATEICONS

Create Icons for configuration files. Default=YES
If Event! is started from CLI iconcreation is always turned off.

Example: CREATICONS=NO

DONOTWAIT

You have to specify this tooltype if you put Event! in your WBStartup 
directory.


To start Event!  with another configuration than "s:Event!.cfg" you have to
save the configuration with enabled iconcreation and start the
configuration just like Event!.  This also works with the
WBStartup-directory.

Alternatively you may hold down the SHIFT-key, click on the configuration
file icon and double-click on Event!'s icon .

@EndNode

@Node "From Shell" "Event!.guide/From Shell"
@Toc "Starting Event!"

    From Shell        

It is advised to put a line like "Run >NIL: Event!" in your
s:UserStartup after REXXMAST.
If you own the Installer-Utility by Commodore, simply click on the
@{"Install Event!" Link "Installation"}-icon and any necessary files
will be copied.

Template: FROM,CX__PRIORITY/N/K,CX__POPKEY/K,CX__POPUP/K,GUIDE/K

FROM (CLI only)

Event! configuration, defaults to S:Event!.CFG

CX__PRIORITY/N/K  

Priority of Event! within the commodities queue. Default: 0.

CX__POPUP/K

Open configuration window after startup. Default: YES.

Example: CX__POPUP=NO

CX__POPKEY <key>

Commodities @{"Hotkey" Link "HotKeys"} definition for showing the userinterface.  Default:
"lalt e".

Example: CX__POPKEY=ctrl lcommand e

GUIDE/K <guidefile>

Path and FileName for the AmigaGuide online help file.

Example: GUIDE=SYS:Utilities/Guides/Event!.guide

@EndNode

@Node "Important Note" "Event!.guide/Important Note"
@Toc "Starting Event!"

    Important Note        

Make sure that the ARexx-Servertask ("RexxMast") is already running
when you start Event! at system startup from s:User-Startup or the
WBStartup directory. To ensure this, start the "RexxMast" command BEFORE
Event!, either by placing it before Event! in your user-startup or by
using the ToolType STARTPRI=1 for RexxMast in your WBStartup.

@EndNode

@Node "The Main Configuration Window" "Event!.guide/The Main Configuration Window"
@Toc "Main"

The Main Configuration Window

This window is used to configure Event!  and to work on whole
event-definitions, like creating a new editable event or deleting it, etc.
This window opens

->  on startup if you did not specify "CX_POPUP=NO" 

->  if  you select to show interface on Event!  in the Commodities
    Exchange utility.  

->  if  you  select  "Open  Configuration Window" from the clock's
    menu 

->  if  you  press  the  CX_POPKEY  sequence.  Default is "LALT e"
    which  means  you  have  to  hold  down the left alt key and press
    "e".   The  selected  popkey is displayed in the title of Event!'s
    main configuration window.  

-> if you send CTRL-F to the main task.  

-> if you start Event! though it is already running.  

@EndNode

@Node "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets" "Event!.guide/The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"
@Toc "Main"

The Main Configuration Window contains the following gadgets:

The list of event definitions      : @{"Event Definitions" Link "Event Definitions"}

Create a new event definition      : @{"New" Link "New"} 
Edit an event definition           : @{"Edit..." Link "Edit..."} 
Cut an event definition            : @{"Cut" Link "Cut"} 
Duplicate an event definition      : @{"Clone" Link "Clone"} 
Execute an event definition        : @{"Test" Link "Test"} 
Paste an event definition          : @{"Paste" Link "Paste"} 

Move an event definition to the top: @{"Top" Link "TopUpDownBottom"} 
Move an event definiton upwards    : @{"Up" Link "TopUpDownBottom"} 
Move an event definition downwards : @{"Down" Link "TopUpDownBottom"} 
Move an event definition to the end: @{"Bottom" Link "TopUpDownBottom"} 
 
Specify the log file to use        : @{"Logfile" Link "Logfile"} 
Toggle small/verbose log files     : @{"Tiny Logs" Link "Tiny Logs"} 

Set type of clock display          : @{"ClockType" Link "ClockType"} 
Toggle following to public screens : @{"Follow to Active PubScreen" Link "Follow to Active PubScreen"} 
Use clock's screen's font for clock: @{"Use Screen's Font for Clock" Link "Use Screen's Font for Clock"} 
Specify clock's font               : @{"Specify..." Link "Specify..."} 

Set main task's priority           : @{"Main Task Priority" Link "Main Task Priority"} 
Set event checking task's priority : @{"Check Task Priority" Link "Check Task Priority"} 

Save configuration                 : @{"Save" Link "Save"} 
Hide the main configuration window : @{"Hide" Link "Hide"} 
Quit Event! -NO!!!                 : @{"Quit" Link "Quit"} 

@EndNode


@Node "Event Definitions" "Event!.guide/Event Definitions"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Event Definitions        

This is a listview gadget showing the list of events you can operate on
with the surrounding gadgets in the same box.  You have to select an event
in this gadget before you can operate on it.

@EndNode

@Node "New" "Event!.guide/New"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

   New         

Use this gadget to create a new event.  If you have selected an event in
the definitions gadget the new event will be inserted right below it
otherwise at the end of the list.

Note:  The name of the new event will be set to "New Event".  All other
string gadgets will be left empty.  The new event is set to occur "Never"
but if you select to let it occur "On Time" you will find that the
occurance date is set to the current time with seconds zero and the day of
week and year as wildcards.  The only set action flag is to bring the
clockwindow to front.

@EndNode

@Node "Edit..." "Event!.guide/Edit..."
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Edit         

If you select this gadget you will open @{"The Event Edit Window" Link "The Event Edit Window"}

Note:  If the event-edit window is already open this gadget will first work like
pressing the @{"Ok" Link "Ok"} gadget in the event edit window. Then if the
definition in the event edit window is o.k. it will allow you to edit the selected
event.

@EndNode


@Node "Cut" "Event!.guide/Cut"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

   Cut

Copies the selected event definition to the clipboard in ASCII format.
Afterwards the event definition is erased.  You can use the event
definition in other clipboard supporting programs like CED, if you use it
together with CB2REXX, a freely distributable utility. Note: CygnusEd 3.5
supports the clipboard anyway, so you don't need CB2REXX.

@EndNode

@Node "Clone" "Event!.guide/Clone"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

 Clone         

Duplicates  the  selected  event  and  inserts  it right below the
selected one. The copy becomes the currently selected event.  

@EndNode

@Node "Test" "Event!.guide/Test"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

 Test         

Executes the action part of the selected event.  

@EndNode

@Node "Paste" "Event!.guide/Paste"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

   Paste         

Paste an event (or even an ARexx Command) from the clipboard.  

@EndNode

@Node "TopUpDownBottom" "Event!.guide/TopUpDownBottom"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Top / Up / Down / Bottom   

Moves the selected event in the list.  

@EndNode

@Node "Logfile" "Event!.guide/Logfile"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Logfile         

In this gadget you can enter a filename where you want the logfile written
to.  Leave this empty to disable logging.

@EndNode

@Node "Tiny Logs" "Event!.guide/Tiny Logs"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Tiny Logs        

This checkbox determines the amount of information written to the logfile.
If you select "Tiny Logs" only date, time, name and cause of the occured
events will be written to, otherwise also the _whole_ event definition.

@EndNode

@Node "ClockType" "Event!.guide/ClockType"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    ClockType         

Select this to select the kind of clock you want Event!  to display.  You
can select between "No Clock", "Clock Only" and "Clock And Mem" which
should be selfexplanatory.

Note:  If you select "No Clock" and an event occurs which should display a
message the clockwindow will open for the time the message is displayed and
disappear afterwards immediately again.


@EndNode

@Node "Follow to Active PubScreen" "Event!.guide/Follow to Active PubScreen"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Follow to Active PubScreen      

Since Amiga OS Release 2 programs may open their screens in public mode
which means that other programs can open their windows on it in a system
conform manner.  If you select this gadget, Event!'s clockwindow will
follow to the active public screen.  Note that some programs only support
visitor windows in a dirty way.  CED 2.12 is one of this programs which
guru sometimes when a visitorwindow is on it, but the screen should be
closed.  It is not advised to run CED in public screen mode.


@EndNode

@Node "Use Screen's Font for Clock" "Event!.guide/Use Screen's Font for Clock"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Use Screen's Font for Clock     

If this gadget is selected the clock window uses the font of the screen it
is on.

@EndNode

@Node "Specify..." "Event!.guide/Specify..."
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Specify...         

This gadget is mutually exclusive to the @{"Use Screen's Font for Clock" Link "Use Screen's Font for Clock"} gadget.
If you select this gadget a fontrequester will pop up and ask you for the
font the clock should use.  Note that proportional fonts are accepted but
not advisable since mostly there'll be some space left in the right part of
the clock.  Note also that you have to select the "Use Screen's Font for
Clock" gadget first if you want to select a new font.

@EndNode

@Node "Main Task Priority" "Event!.guide/Main Task Priority"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Main Task Priority       

This is the priority Event!'s main task runs with.  The main task does
everything but checking if an event occured and creating the string for the
clockwindow which is done by the event check task.  The main task also
executes occuring events and displays the time and date in the clockwindow.
This is also the priority CLI commands will be executed at.


@EndNode

@Node "Check Task Priority" "Event!.guide/Check Task Priority"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Check Task Priority       

See @{"Main Task Priority" Link "Main Task Priority"}  

@EndNode

@Node "Save" "Event!.guide/Save"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Save

Saves the configuration to the current configuration file which is also
displayed in the screentitle of the window.

@EndNode

@Node "Hide" "Event!.guide/Hide"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Hide         

Hides the main configuration window user interface.  Besides, same as the
closegadget.

@EndNode

@Node "Quit" "Event!.guide/Quit"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Gadgets"

    Quit         

    Guess what! 


@EndNode

@Node "The Main Configuration Window Menus" "Event!.guide/The Main Configuration Window Menus"
@Toc "Main"

Menu Items in the Main Configuration Window

Project Menu:

Open a configuration file          : @{"Open" Link "Open..."} 
Append a configuration file        : @{"Append..." Link "Append..."} 
Execute an ARexx-script            : @{"Execute ARexx-Script" Link "Execute ARexx-Script"} 
Save configuration                 : @{"Save" Link "MSave"} 
Save configuration as...           : @{"Save as" Link "Save as"} 
Hide the main configuration window : @{"Hide" Link "MHide"} 
Display About-window               : @{"About" Link "MAbout"} 
No description available           : @{"Quit" Link "MQuit"} 

Edit Menu:

Remove all event definitions       : @{"Remove All Events" Link "Remove All Events"} 
Cut an event definition to clip    : @{"Cut" Link "MCut"} 
Copy an event definition to clip   : @{"Copy" Link "MCopy"} 
Paste an event definition from clip: @{"Paste" Link "MPaste"} 
Erase an event definition          : @{"Erase" Link "MErase"} 

Special Menu:

Snapshot window's position         : @{"Snapshot window" Link "Snapshot window"} 
Toggle creation of icons           : @{"Create Icons" Link "Create Icons"} 

@EndNode

@Node "Open..." "Event!.guide/Open..."
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Open...         

Load a new configuration.  Note that the previous configuration will be
lost!

IMPORTANT Note:  Config reading is done asynchronously.  So you should wait
for the config reading to complete before you save it.  If you don't,
you'll save a incomplete configuration.

Note also:  Event!-configuration files are simply ARexx-Scripts.  Due to
limits of ARexx you cannot execute scriptfiles containing a space, so
Event!  configuration filenames mustn't contain spaces, too.  Since many
users will extract their Event!-archives to "Ram Disk:", Event!  converts
this volume name to "Ram:"

@EndNode

@Node "Append..." "Event!.guide/Append..."
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

    Append...         

Same as "Open...", but doesn't erase the eventlist before executing the
script.

@EndNode

@Node "Execute ARexx-Script" "Event!.guide/Execute ARexx-Script..."
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

    Execute ARexx-Script...        

Internally nearly the same as "Append..." since configurations are
ARexx-Scripts.  The only difference is that "Append..." tries to load the
corresponding icon for reuse when saving the configuration with icons.


@EndNode

@Node "MSave" "Event!.guide/MSave"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Save         

Same as the @{"Save" Link "Save"}-Gadget.  

@EndNode

@Node "Save as" "Event!.guide/Save as"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Save as        

A requester will ask you for the name of the file you want the
configuration to be saved to.  If you select "Ok" in the requester this
name will become the new current configuration name.

@EndNode

@Node "MHide" "Event!.guide/MHide"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Hide         

Same as the  @{"Hide" Link "Hide"}-Gadget.  

@EndNode

@Node "MAbout" "Event!.guide/MAbout"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   About         

Displays some information about Event!.  If you registered and own a
keyfile, your name and address will be displayed as well.

@EndNode

@Node "MQuit" "Event!.guide/MQuit"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Quit         

    Don't do it ;-) 

@EndNode

@Node "Remove All Events" "Event!.guide/Remove All Events"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Remove All Events       

This will erase all eventdefinitions in the list.  


@EndNode

@Node "MCut" "Event!.guide/MCut"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Cut         

See gadget @{"Cut" Link "Cut"}.

@EndNode

@Node "MCopy" "Event!.guide/MCopy"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Copy         

Like @{"Cut" Link "MCut"} but the event is not erased.  

@EndNode

@Node "MPaste" "Event!.guide/MPaste"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Paste         

Paste an event (or even an ARexx Command) from the clipboard.  

@EndNode

@Node "MErase" "Event!.guide/Erase"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Erase         

Delete selected event.  No copy to the clipboard is done.  An in this way
deleted event can't be recalled.

@EndNode

@Node "Snapshot window" "Event!.guide/Snapshot window"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Snapshot window        

Saves the position of the window to the Text Gadgets.  These are the
positions that will be saved to the configuration file.  Do not mix this up
with Event!'s remembering of window positions which is only for the current
session.

@EndNode

@Node "Create Icons" "Event!.guide/Create Icons"
@Toc "The Main Configuration Window Menus"

   Create Icons

The state of this menu items's checkmark determines if Event!'s
configuration files are saved with icons.

@EndNode

@Node "The Event Edit Window" "Event!.guide/The Event Edit Window"
@Toc "Main"

This window allows you to edit an event definition.  You can open it by
selecting an event and clicking on "Edit..." in the main configuration
window.

@{"The Event Edit Window Gadgets" Link "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"} are divided into three parts:

The left side of the window contains the gadgets describing the conditions
when an event will occur.

The right side of the window contains the gadgets describing the actions
executed if an event occurs.

The remaining gadgets have general functions, i.e. naming the event or
confirming the event definition.


@EndNode

@Node "The Event Edit Window Gadgets" "Event!.guide/The Event Edit Gadgets"
@Toc "Main"

   The Event Edit Window Gadgets

Left Side: Conditions

Specify condition type            : @{"Occur" Link "Occur"} 
Define time conditions            : @{"The Time Definition Gadgets" Link "The Time Definition Gadgets"} 
File/directory to supervise       : @{"Change of File" Link "Change of File"} 
Notification tolerance time       : @{"Tolerance Secs" Link "Tolerance Secs"} 
This event's hotkey               : @{"Action Hotkey" Link "Action Hotkey"} 

Right Side: Actions

 Audible beep                     : @{"Audible Beep" Link "Audible Beep"} 
 Visible beep                     : @{"Visible Beep" Link "Visible Beep"} 
 Clock to front                   : @{"Clockwindow to Front" Link "Clockwindow to Front"} 
 Clock's screen to front          : @{"Clockwindows screen to front" Link "Clockwindows screen to front"} 
 Occur only once                  : @{"Only Once" Link "Only Once"} 
 Do not log occurance             : @{"Do Not Log" Link "Do Not Log"} 
 Erase event when occured         : @{"Kill When Done (NOT saved)" Link "Kill When Done (NOT saved)"} 
 Display/Request Action           : @{"Display Type" Link "Display Type"} 
 Run/RX/Melody Action             : @{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"} 

General gadgets:

Specify the event's name          : @{"Name" Link "Name"} 
Remember changes                  : @{"Ok" Link "Ok"} 
Like "Ok" but goes to prev. defin.: @{"Ok & Prev" Link "Ok & Prev"} 
Like "Ok" but goes to next defin. : @{"Ok & Next" Link "Ok & Next"} 
Execute event definition          : @{"Test it!" Link "Test it!"}
Forget changes                    : @{"Cancel" Link "Cancel"}

@EndNode

@Node "Occur" "Event!.guide/Occur"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Occur         

This is a cycle gadget. You can select between: 

    "Never":    The  event  will  only  occur  when  "Test"-ed  or the
    specified hotkey is pressed.  

    "On   Time":   The  event  will occur when the specified time (see
    @{"The Time Definition Gadgets" Link "The Time Definition Gadgets"}) is matching. 

    "On  Notification" The event will occur when the specified file or
    directory is changed (see @{"Change of File" Link "Change of File"}).


@EndNode

@Node "The Time Definition Gadgets" "Event!.guide/The Time Definition Gadgets"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   The Time Definition Gadgets      

An "On Time" event will only occur if all the time gadgets match the
current time.  By choosing the WeekDay / Day / Month / Year" gadgets you
specify the date an event will occur.  The "Hour / Minute / Seconds" you
choose the time an event will occur.  If the checkbox at the right side of
a time gadget isn't checked, Event!  will not compare the current time to
this part of the time definition, it is a "wildcard" and its gadget is
disabled.  With this method you can define events that occur every hour or
every week or the first of every month, etc.

Hint: 

If you want several events use the same action part of an event you can
define multiple events using the "TEST" ARexx command to start the action
part of this event.  This can be useful if you want i.e.  an event occuring
every Monday, Wednesday and Friday.  Thus, if you want to change the action
you have to change only one event.  But be careful:  ARexx commands for
Event!  are first parsed by the ARexx-parser and then by ReadArgs().  For
further information see "If 'Command Type' is ARexx" in the @{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"}
description.

@EndNode

@Node "Change of File" "Event!.guide/Change of File"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Change of File       

In this gadget you can enter a file or directory name.  The event will
occur if "On Notification" is set and the given file or directory changes.

Deeper Information:  This uses the notification mechanism of dos.library
V37+.  This doesn't work on all filesystems.  With the OFS and FFS in
Kickstart V2.0 and the RAM:  Disk V37+ it works fine anyway.  I am sorry it
is not possible to use wildcards or to determine which file in a directory
changed cause there is no mechanism provided for this in the current
release of dos.library.  ;-(

@EndNode


@Node "Tolerance Secs" "Event!.guide/Tolerance Secs"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

Tolerance Secs

Many programs do more than one file/directory accesses within a very short
time, for which only a single notification event is desired.
I.e. if CygnusED has switched on "Safe saves" it first saves to a temporary
file, afterwards it deletes the old file and then renames the temporary
file. If you had set a notification to this file this would result in
2 notifications. To prevent this you can specify with this gadget, how
many seconds Event! tolerates notifications for the notification object
without executing the event. As soon as no notifications for the
specified time occured, the event will be executed.

This feature is also very useful for notifications to the inbound-directory
of your system since TrapDoor also works with temporary files.

@EndNode

@Node "Action Hotkey" "Event!.guide/Action Hotkey"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Action Hotkey        

This defines a @{"Hotkey" Link "Hotkeys"} for executing the action part of an event using an
input description.

You may define a hotkey for every event, so that you can execute them
manually, without having to bring up Event!'s intuition interface. A
hotkey start overrides even the @{"Occur" Link "Occur"}- "Never"cycle gadget
setting.

@EndNode

@Node "Audible Beep" "Event!.guide/Audible Beep"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

    Audible Beep        

It   beeps  when  the  event occurs.  The audio.device is used for
this.   If  no  beep  can  be  heard,   Event!    couldn't  get  a
channel   because  it was already allocated. Or you've just got to
turn up the volume! ;-) 

@EndNode

@Node "Visible Beep" "Event!.guide/Visible Beep"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

    Visible Beep        

The screen will flash.  

Note: 

This one uses the intuition function DisplayBeep().  In later releases than
OS2.0 of the system software you will be able to choose what happens if
DisplayBeep() is called.  So there might be no flashing but a sound for
example.

@EndNode

@Node "Clockwindow to Front" "Event!.guide/Clockwindow to Front"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Clockwindow to Front       

Bring the clockwindow to front if it is open.  You should set this for
events that display messages in the clockwindow.  It is also advisable that
you bring the window sometimes (i.e.  once a minute to front" in case it is
obscured by other windows.

@EndNode

@Node "Clockwindows screen to front" "Event!.guide/Clockwindows screen to front"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Clockwindow's screen to front      

Bring the screen of the clockwindow to front if it is open.  

@EndNode

@Node "Only Once" "Event!.guide/Only Once"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Only Once        

Let this event occur only once while this Event!  is running or the event
is changed.

@EndNode

@Node "Do Not Log" "Event!.guide/Do Not Log"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Do Not Log       

Do not write it to the logfile when this event occured.  

@EndNode

@Node "Kill When Done (NOT saved)" "Event!.guide/Kill When Done (NOT saved)"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Kill When Done (NOT saved)     

The  event  will be erased after it was executed. Events with this
flag  only  exist until they occur or Event! is terminated because
they are NOT saved when you save the configuration.  

@EndNode

@Node "Display Type" "Event!.guide/Display Type"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Display Type        

This can be either "ClockWindow" which means the "Display String" will be
displayed in the clockwindow or "Requester" which means a requester will be
opened, display "DisplayString" and then waits to be satisfied.

The Meaning of the Display String...    

  ...is predetermined by 'Display Type'.  


If 'Display Type' is 'ClockWindow'...     

the given string will be displayed in the clockwindow.  If the text fits
into the clockwindow, it will simply be displayed for 5 seconds (default) -
if it does not, it is scrolled.  If the clock is turned off when a text is
about to be displayed , a window of "clock only" size is opened for the
time necessary.

While displaying messages the user interface is still usable, pending
events are queued up and executed right after displaying the text is
finished.

You can change the values for the displaytime and the scrolling speed, the
template is:


    [DisplayTime,[ScrollDelay,]]Your Text 


Examples (do not use the quotes): 


    "Hello World!!!!" 

This one displays the string "Hello World!!!!" for 5 seconds if the string
fits in the clockwindow, otherwise it scrolls it with a delay of 1/50 s
between scrolling moves.  Note that 5 and 1 are the default values for
displaytime and speed.



    "4,0,Hello World!!!!" 

This one displays the text for 4 secs if it fits in the clockwindow,
otherwise the text is scrolled with no (zero) delay.



    "4,Hello World!!!!" 

This one also displays it for 4 secs if it fits in the clockwindow, but
otherwise the text is scrolled with the 1/50s default delay, since no
option was specified for this...



    "42 is the answer!" 

This example again displays the text with the default values since there is
no comma right after the numbers.


Note:  I like a scrolldelay of zero, but on Amigas being faster than
A4000/40s this might be *too* fast, besides there's no CPU-time left for
other tasks when scrolling with a zero-delay and a high Event!  main task
priority.


Technical Information:  Displaying messages is done asynchronously.  If you
switch screens/ windowtypes, fonts, or you do anything else that reopens
the window the message will be displayed *completely* again.  This avoids
that you miss a message or parts of it due to screenswitches and/or font
changes.


If 'Display Type' is 'Requester'...

...the given text will be displayed in a requester.  You can separate
multiple lines by using a semicolon, i.e:

    "It's not a bug,;it's a feature!" 

@EndNode

@Node "Command Type" "Event!.guide/Command Type"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Command Type        

Command Type can be either "CLI Command", "ARexx Command" or "Melody".


The meaning of the 'Command String'...    

 ...is predetermined by 'Command Type':


If 'Command Type' is CLI Command    

---> it will be executed.  Output will be sent to an Amiga OS Release 2
autoclose window, that means the window will be only opened, if the
executed command really does output.  You can redirect the output by using
">" i.e.

    "run >NIL: copy ram:Disk.info sys:storage/ram.inf" 

Multiple CLI commands can be separated by ";" 


This way it is possible to set stack and current directory by using the
"stack" and "cd" commands.  Example:

    "stack 11111;cd devs:;dir;stack;wait 5" 

Note:  The wait command prevents the outputwindow to close immediately
after the "stack" command is executed.

Hint:  The string is not executed asyncronously so you have to preappend
"run " if you don't want to delay Event!'s main task.  However if you don't
"run " commands you will not loose any occuring events, since the event
check task marks those events for later execution.


If 'Command Type' is 'ARexx Command'    

---> the given string will either be interpreted as an ARexx script or if
it is in quotes as an ARexx command.

Default  extension  for  scripts is .evt
Default port for commands is: EVENT! 

NOTE: 
You've got to enter ARexx commands for Event!  very carefully since they
are parsed first by ARexx AND then by the Amiga OS2.0 ReadArgs() function.
To TEST an event called "Full Hour Beep-2" for example, you should enter
'TEST "Full Hour Beep-2"'.  The outside quotes make ARexx execute the
instead of trying to load a script from disk.  The quotation marks are
necessary for ReadArgs() because the event name contains spaces.  If the
parameter of the "TEST"-command would contain an * or a " you would have to
use * as an escape char.  For example, instead of 'TEST "Poll*"' you would
have to write 'TEST "Poll**"'


If 'Command Type' is 'Melody'     

---> a list of notes to play are accepted as parameters, separated by
spaces.  Each note consists of a period and a duration, separated by a
comma.  Sounds difficult?  Here is an example (don't type in the quotes:)

    "381,10 0,1 381,15 339,15 381,15 285,15 302,30"

      D    Pause D      E      D      H      F#

The duration must be given in ticks (1/50s), the periods are special amiga
values.  You can look these up in the following table:

    +----+------+
    |Note|Period|
    |  C |  428 |
    | C# |  404 |
    |  D |  381 |
    | D# |  360 |
    |  E |  339 |
    |  F |  320 |
    | F# |  302 |
    |  G |  285 |
    | G# |  269 |
    |  A |  254 |
    | A# |  240 |
    |  H |  226 |
    +----+------+


Double the value to let the tone sound one octave lower, halve it to do the
opposite.

Don't expect too much from this option.  This is not a soundtracker clone
;-) Just to remind you of special events.  (You probably know the funny
little sounds PCs sometimes let out.)

If you want to play real samples, we recommend the use of 'upd' or similar
tools.  You can perfectly control them via Event!


@EndNode

@Node "Name" "Event!.guide/Name"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Name         

Nearly forgot this one!  ;) Defines the name of an event.  This name is
displayed in the eventlist and can be used to operate on the event via
ARexx.

@EndNode

@Node "Ok" "Event!.guide/Ok"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Ok         

Checks the changes made in the event edit window and closes it if
everything is fine.  If a bad @{"hotkey" Link "HotKeys"}  or notification file is given the
display will beep and the stringgadget with the bad content will be
activated.  If Event!  is out of memory for allocating the event definition
Event!  will also beep and keep the window open.  When you are that much
out of memory you have to shut down other events or you'll have to get rid
off the event edit window with the Cancel/Close gadget.

@EndNode

@Node "Ok & Prev" "Event!.guide/Ok & Prev"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Ok & Prev       

Same as @{"Ok" Link "Ok"}, but will not close the event edit window, but edit the
previous event in the event list.


@EndNode

@Node "Ok & Next" "Event!.guide/Ok & Next"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Ok & Next       

Same as @{"Ok" Link "Ok"}, but will not close the event edit window, but
edit the next event in the event list.

@EndNode

@Node "Test it!" "Event!.guide/Test it!"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Test it!        

Execute the action part of the edited event.  Also checks @{"hotkey" Link "HotKeys"} and
notification file like "Ok".

@EndNode

@Node "Cancel" "Event!.guide/Cancel"
@Toc "The Event Edit Window Gadgets"

   Cancel         

Loose  changes  on  the  current  edited event and close the event
edit window.  Same as the closegadget.  

@EndNode

@Node "The Event Edit Windows Menu" "Event!.guide/The Event Edit Windows Menu"
@Toc "Main"

  The Event Edit Window's Menu     

    "Ok"  &  "Cancel"  work  like  the  gadgets  with  the same names.

    "Snapshot  Window"  works  like  @{"Snapshot window" Link "Snapshot window"} from the main
    configuration window but for the event edit window of course.  

@EndNode


@Node "The Clock Window" "Event!.guide/The Clock Window"
@Toc "Main"

    The Clock Window       

If  this  window  is  activated  it  will display the current date
instead of the current time. The clock window's appearance depends
on the following gadgets of the @{"The Main Configuration Window" Link "The Main Configuration Window"}:

 @{"ClockType" Link "ClockType"} 
 @{"Follow to Active PubScreen" Link "Follow to Active PubScreen"} 
 @{"Use Screen's Font for Clock" Link "Use Screen's Font for Clock"} 
 @{"Specify..." Link "Specify..."} 

To set the position of the clock window select "Snapshot Window" from
the @{"Clock Window Menu" Link "The Clock Window Menu"}.

@EndNode

@Node "The Clock Window Gadgets" "Event!.guide/The Clock Window Gadgets"
@Toc "Main"

   The Clock Window Gadgets      


Closegadget         

It is invisible, but works.  It is at the top left corner of the clock.
When it is pressed the clockwindow will disappear for a few seconds from
the current screen.  This allows you to close a public screen where the
Event!-clock is on.  This is also useful when intuition attempts to reset
the Workbench.


The Depth Gadget       

    ... is also invisible but works.  

@EndNode


@Node "The Clock Window Menu" "Event!.guide/The Clock Window Menu"
@Toc "Main"

   The Clock Window Menu


Snapshot Window        

    Snapshot  the  current  clockwindow  position  to the textgadgets.
    The clockwindow will reopen the next time at this position.  

Open Configuration Window       

    Open the main configuration window.  


@EndNode

@Node "Controlling Event!'s gadgets with keys" "Controlling Event!'s gadgets with keys"
@Toc "Main"

   Controlling Event!'s gadgets with keys     

Most of the gadgets in Event!  can be controlled with keyboard shortcuts.
These gadgets have an underlined letter in their name.  Press this
alphanumeric key instead of the gadget.  In the CYCLE, the LISTVIEW- and
the SLIDER gadgets you can use the SHIFT key together with the key to make
a backward selection.  The checkboxes in the time definition part of the
event edit window can be toggled with the CTRL key and the shortcutkey of
the related gadget.  Of course you can't use keyboard shortcuts for
disabled gadgets.

Since Event! V1.2 you can additionally select events in the event listview
with the cursor up/down keys and edit them with the return key. To
close windows you may now use the Escape key.

@EndNode


@Node "Hotkeys" "Event!.guide/Hotkeys"
@ToC  "Main"

   Hotkeys

Hotkeys are descriptions of keyboard sequences and done via Commodities.  A
hotkey may look like this:  (everything is case insensitive)

      [<qualifier> [<qualifier>...]] <key>

      Qualifier keywords

        alt           either Alt key
        ralt          right Alt key
        lalt          left Alt key
        shift         either Shift key
        rshift        right Shift key
        lshift        left Shift key
        capslock      Caps Lock key
        rcommand      right Amiga key
        lcommand      left Amiga key
        Control       Control key
        numericpad    Enables the use of a key on the numeric keypad
        rbutton       Click the right mouse button
        midbutton     Click the middle mouse button
        leftbutton    Click the left mouse button
        newprefs      Preferences changed
        diskremoved   Disk removed
        diskinserted  Disk inserted


      Keys

        a .. z, 0 .. 9, etc.   Normal keys
        f1 .. f10              Function keys
        up, down, left, right  Cursor keys
        help                   Help key
        del                    Delete key
        return                 Return key
        enter                  Enter key (MUST be combined with 'numericpad'!)
        backspace              Backspace key
        esc                    Escape key
        space                  Space key
        comma                  Comma key
        upstroke               Upstroke key


      Examples

        lalt ralt enter
        ramiga f10
        alt x

NOTE:  Choose your hot keys CAREFULLY, because commodities.library has a
high priority in the input events chain (i.e.  will override existing
definitions).

@EndNode


@Node "The ARexx Interface" "The ARexx Interface"
@Toc "Main"

   The ARexx Interface.       

Event!  has a complex ARexx interface.  You can send all the following
commands to Event!  while it is running.  ARexx is also used for the
configuration, which is saved in ASCII and can also be modified by the
user.  When using an ARexx command also look up the description of the
corresponding gadget or menu item.

What a surprise, Event!'s ARexx port is named EVENT!.  And, yes, this is
case sensitive.

Note:  It is advised to use "options results" in your AREXX Scripts since
some of the commands return resultstrings.  Most of the commands also
return resultcodes.  If no error occured then rc will be zero.

Note also:  ARexx-Commands for Event!  are first parsed by the ARexx-parser
and then by ReadArgs().  For further information see "If 'Command Type' is ARexx"
in the @{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"} section.


 @{"The TellEvent! command" Link "The TellEvent! command"}

ARexx Commands

 @{"Defining events" Link "Defining events"}

 @{"Window Position Commands" Link "Window Position Commands"}

 @{"Clock type specification" Link "Clock type specification"}

 @{"Task Priority Commands" Link "Internals"}

 @{"Log File Commands" Link "Log File Commands"}

 @{"Operations on events" Link "Operations on events"}

 @{"Configuration File Operations" Link "Configuration File Operations"}

 @{"Others" Link "Others"}

@EndNode


@Node "The TellEvent! command" "Event!.guide/The TellEvent! command"
@ToC  "The ARexx Interface"

   The TellEvent! command

The Event!  archive contains a command called TellEvent!.  It can be used
to send commands to Event!'s ARexx port.

Examples: 

    TellEvent! 'BAN 5' 

    TellEvent! 'QUIT' 

    TellEvent! 'REQUEST "Just another test!"' 

    TellEvent! 'BEEP BLINK DISPLAY "2,0,Just another test!"' 

    TellEvent! 'EVENT "Poll UUCP" ONTIME WHEN "#3 #24 #6 #92 0 3 30"
     RUN "run mail:scripts/polluucp"'

Note that you have to write the whole event definition in a SINGLE line!

Note also:  ARexx commands for Event!  are first parsed by the ARexx parser
and then by ReadArgs().  For further information see "If 'Command Type' is ARexx"
in the @{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"} section.


@EndNode

@Node "Defining events" "Event!.guide/Defining events"
@ToC  "The ARexx Interface"

   Defining events

Example: 

     '@{"EVENT" Link "EVENT_K"} "Poll UUCP"
      @{"ONTIME" Link "NEVER_S ONTIME_S ONNOTIFY_S"}
      @{"WHEN" Link "WHEN_K"} "#3 #24 #6 #92 0 3 30"
      @{"NOTIFY" Link "NOTIFY_K"} ""
      @{"HOTKEY" Link "HOTKEY_K"} "ctrl lshift u"
      @{"DISPLAY" Link "DISPLAY_K"} "5,0,Polling UUCP-Mail!"
      @{"RUN" Link "RUN_K"} "run mail:scripts/polluucp"'

This will define an event called "Poll UUCP". It will occur every day at
0:03:30h or if its @{"hotkey" Link "HotKeys"}  "ctrl lshift u" is pressed. When running the
script "mail:scripts/polluucp" it will display "Polling UUCP-Mail!" in the
clock's window.


Keywords for defining events:
-----------------------------

General:

 The event's name        : @{"EVENT/K" Link "EVENT_K"}

Condition part:

 Occurance               : @{"NEVER/S ONTIME/S ONNOTIFY/S" Link "NEVER_S ONTIME_S ONNOTIFY_S"}
 Time condition          : @{"WHEN/K" Link "WHEN_K"}
 File to supervise       : @{"NOTIFY/K" Link "NOTIFY_K"}
 Notification Tolerance  : @{"NOTIFYTOLERANCE/K/N" Link "NOTIFYTOLERANCE_K_N"}
 Hotkey for event        : @{"HOTKEY/K" Link "HOTKEY_K"}

Action part:

 Audible beep            : @{"BEEP/S" Link "BEEP_S"}
 Visible beep            : @{"BLINK/S" Link "BLINK_S"}
 Clock to front          : @{"WINFRONT/S" Link "WINFRONT_S"}
 Clock's screen to front : @{"SCREENFRONT/S" Link "SCREENFRONT_S"}
 Occur only once         : @{"ONCE/S" Link "ONCE_S"}
 Do not log occurance    : @{"DONOTLOG/S" Link "DONOTLOG_S"}
 Erase event when occured: @{"KILLDONE/S" Link "KILLDONE_S"}
 Display text in clock   : @{"DISPLAY/K" Link "DISPLAY_K"}
 Put up requester w/text : @{"REQUEST/K" Link "REQUEST_K"}
 Run a CLI command       : @{"RUN/K" Link "RUN_K"}
 Execute an ARexx command: @{"RX/K" Link "RX_K"}
 Play specified melody   : @{"MELODY/K" Link "MELODY_K"}


@EndNode


@Node "EVENT_K" "Event!.guide/EVENT/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

  EVENT/K

Defines the name of an event.  You must use this keyword to define an
event.  All the following keywords are optional since they will use default
values.

@EndNode

@Node "NEVER_S ONTIME_S ONNOTIFY_S" "Event!.guide/NEVER/S ONTIME/S ONNOTIFY/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

    NEVER/S 

The event is to occur never.  Default when defining a new event.  

    ONTIME/S 

The event is to occur depending on time.  

    ONNOTIFY/S 

The event is to occur depending on file notification.  

@EndNode

@Node "WHEN_K" "Event!.guide/WHEN/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   WHEN/K

Defines the time schedule when an @{"ONTIME" Link "NEVER_S ONTIME_S ONNOTIFY_S"} event occurs.  

The template is (same order as in the user interface): 

<weekday> <day> <month> <year> <hour> <minute> <second> 

If a '#' preceeds a value, it is saved but not actually used. This
has the same meaning as an unset checkmark for a time condition in
the event edit window.

@EndNode

@Node "NOTIFY_K" "Event!.guide/NOTIFY/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   NOTIFY/K

Defines the template for file notification.

Will only have an effect if @{"ONNOTIFY/S" Link "NEVER_S ONTIME_S ONNOTIFY_S"} is set.

@EndNode

@Node "NOTIFYTOLERANCE_K_N" "Event!.guide/NOTIFYTOLERANCE/K/N"
@ToC  "Defining events"

NOTIFYTOLERANCE/K/N

Specify the @{"Tolerance Secs" Link "Tolerance Secs"} for the
@{"Notify" Link "NOTIFY_K"}-argument.

@EndNode

@Node "HOTKEY_K" "Event!.guide/HOTKEY/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   HOTKEY/K

Defines a @{"hotkey" Link "HotKeys"} for the starting this event.  

@EndNode

@Node "BEEP_S" "Event!.guide/BEEP/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   BEEP/S

Creates an audible beep. Equals "MELODY 400,20".  

@EndNode

@Node "BLINK_S" "Event!.guide/BLINK/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   BLINK/S

Flashes all screens.  

@EndNode

@Node "WINFRONT_S" "Event!.guide/WINFRONT/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   WINFRONT/S

Pops the clock window to front each time the event is executed.  

@EndNode

@Node "SCREENFRONT_S" "Event!.guide/SCREENFRONT/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   SCREENFRONT/S

Pops the screen the clock window is currently on to front each time the
event is executed.

@EndNode

@Node "ONCE_S" "Event!.guide/ONCE/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   ONCE/S

Disables but does not delete an event after its first execution.  

@EndNode

@Node "DONOTLOG_S" "Event!.guide/DONOTLOG/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   DONOTLOG/S

Do not write logs for this event.  

@EndNode

@Node "KILLDONE_S" "Event!.guide/KILLDONE/S"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   KILLDONE/S

Deletes an event after its first execution.  

@EndNode

@Node "DISPLAY_K" "Event!.guide/DISPLAY/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   DISPLAY/K

Displays the given text in the clock window when the event occurs.  For
further information see "If 'Display Type' is 'ClockWindow'" in the
@{"Display Type" Link "Display Type"} description.

@EndNode

@Node "REQUEST_K" "Event!.guide/REQUEST/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   REQUEST/K

Opens a requester with the given contents.  For further information see
"If 'Display Type' is 'Requester'" in the @{"Display Type" Link "Display Type"} description.

@EndNode

@Node "RUN_K" "Event!.guide/RUN/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   RUN/K

Runs an AmigaDOS command when the event actually occurs.  For further
information see "If 'Command Type' is CLI Command" in the
@{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"} description.

@EndNode

@Node "RX_K" "Event!.guide/RX/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   RX/K

Starts an ARexx script when the event actually occurs.  

For further information see "If 'Command Type' is ARexx" in the @{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"}
description.

@EndNode

@Node "MELODY_K" "Event!.guide/MELODY/K"
@ToC  "Defining events"

   MELODY/K

Plays a melody.  

For further information see "If 'Command Type' is 'Melody'" in the
@{"Command Type" Link "Command Type"} description.

@EndNode

@Node "Window Position Commands" "Event!.guide/Window Position Commands"
@ToC  "The ARexx Interface"

Window Position Commands

Set the left edge open position for the main window      : @{"MainX/N/K <x-pos>" Link "MainX_N_K <x-pos>"}
Set the top  edge open position for the main window      : @{"MainY/N/K <y-pos>" Link "MainY_N_K <y-pos>"}
Set the left edge open position for the event edit window: @{"EventX/N/K <x-pos>" Link "EventX_N_K <x-pos>"}
Set the top  edge open position for the event edit window: @{"EventY/N/K <y-pos>" Link "EventY_N_K <y-pos>"}
Position the clock window at this x-position             : @{"ClockX/N/K <x-pos>" Link "ClockX_N_K <xpos>"}
Position the clock window at this y-position             : @{"ClockY/N/K <y-pos>" Link "ClockY_N_K <ypos>"}

@EndNode

@Node "MainX_N_K <x-pos>" "Event!.guide/MainX/N/K <x-pos>"
@ToC  "Window Position Commands"

   MainX/N/K <x-pos>

Set the X position of the main window.  

@EndNode

@Node "MainY_N_K <y-pos>" "Event!.guide/MainY/N/K <y-pos>"
@ToC  "Window Position Commands"

   MainY/N/K <y-pos>

Set the Y position of the main window.  

@EndNode

@Node "EventX_N_K <x-pos>" "Event!.guide/EventX/N/K <x-pos>"
@ToC  "Window Position Commands"

   EventX/N/K <x-pos>

Set the X position of the window used to edit single events.  

@EndNode

@Node "EventY_N_K <y-pos>" "Event!.guide/EventY/N/K <y-pos>"
@ToC  "Window Position Commands"

   EventY/N/K <y-pos>

Set the Y position of the window used to edit single events.  

Note:  The main and the event edit windows will only be affected by the
positions when you reopen the window.


@EndNode

@Node "ClockX_N_K <xpos>" "Event!.guide/ClockX/N/K <xpos>"
@ToC  "Window Position Commands"

   ClockX/N/K <xpos>

Set the X position of the clock  window.  

@EndNode

@Node "ClockY_N_K <ypos>" "Event!.guide/ClockY/N/K <ypos>"
@ToC  "Window Position Commands"

   ClockY/N/K <ypos>

Set the Y position of the clock  window.  

Note: The clockwindow will move immediately to the new position.  


@EndNode

@Node "Clock type specification" "Event!.guide/Clock type specification"
@ToC  "The ARexx Interface"

     Clock type specification

No clock                             : @{"ClockOff/S" Link "ClockOff_S"}
Display clock                        : @{"ClockOn/S" Link "ClockOn_S"}
Display clock and available memory   : @{"ClockAndMem/S" Link "ClockAndMem_S"}

Set clock's font to its screen's font: @{"SCREENFONT/S" Link "SCREENFONT_S"}
Set clock's font to specified font   : @{"USERFONT/S" Link "USERFONT_S"}
Specify clock's font                 : @{"FONT/K <fontname.font fontheight>" Link "FONT_K <fontname.font fontheight>"}

Do not follow to public screens      : @{"DONTFOLLOW/S" Link "DONTFOLLOW_S"}
Follow to public screens             : @{"FOLLOWSCREENS/S" Link "FOLLOWSCREENS_S"}

@EndNode


@Node "ClockOff_S" "Event!.guide/ClockOff/S"
@ToC  "Clock type specification"

   ClockOff/S

Switch the clock window off.  

@EndNode

@Node "ClockOn_S" "Event!.guide/ClockOn/S"
@ToC  "Clock type specification"

   ClockOn/S

Switch the clock window on if disabled and set it to display the current
time only.

@EndNode

@Node "ClockAndMem_S" "Event!.guide/ClockAndMem/S"
@ToC  "Clock type specification"

   ClockAndMem/S

Switch the clock window on if disabled and set it to display the current
time and free fast and chip memory.

@EndNode

@Node "SCREENFONT_S" "Event!.guide/SCREENFONT/S"
@ToC  "Clock type specification"

   SCREENFONT/S

Use the screen default font in the clock.  

@EndNode

@Node "USERFONT_S" "Event!.guide/USERFONT/S"
